%N A260744 Number of prime juggling patterns of period n using 2 balls.
%C A260744 A juggling pattern is prime if the closed walk corresponding to the pattern in the juggling state graph is a cycle.
%H A260744 Samuel Orellana Mateo, <a href="/A260744/b260744.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..3000</a> (terms 1..135 from Steve Butler).
%H A260744 Esther Banaian, Steve Butler, Christopher Cox, Jeffrey Davis, Jacob Landgraf, and Scarlitte Ponce, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1508.05296">Counting prime juggling patterns</a>, arXiv:1508.05296 [math.CO], 2015.
%H A260744 S. Butler, V. Choi, J. Jeffries, N. McCambridge, A. Morgenstern, and S. Orellana Mateo, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.17284">Enumerating Prime Patterns in Juggling Variations</a>, arXiv:2603.17284 [math.CO], 2026.
%H A260744 Fan Chung and R. L. Graham, <a href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/27642443">Primitive juggling sequences</a>, American Mathematical Monthly 115 (2008), 185-194.
%H A260744 Samuel Orellana Mateo, <a href="https://github.com/Samuel-O-M/prime-juggling-patterns">Prime Juggling Patterns Companion Code</a>, GitHub repository, 2026.
%F A260744 From _Samuel Orellana Mateo_, May 09 2026: (Start)
%F A260744 a(n) = Sum_{t} c_t(n) where the generating function for c_t(n) is G_t(x) = (1/(t(t+1))) * Product_{j=1..t} ((j+1)x^j / (1 - (j+1)x^j)).
%F A260744 Equivalently, c_t(n) = h_t(n) / (t(t+1)), where h_t(n) is defined by the recurrence h_t(n) = (t+1)*[h_{t-1}(n-t) + h_t(n-t)] with h_0(0) = 1. (End)
%e A260744 In siteswap notation, the prime juggling pattern(s) of length one is 2; of length two are 31 and 40; of length three are 330, 411, 420, 501, 600.
%Y A260744 Cf. A260745, A260746, A260752.
